        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Sync and conflict resolution</h2>
        <p class="mb-4">When a list is linked to a remote git repository, GitSorted syncs via standard git fetch, merge, and push operations over HTTPS.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-white mt-6 mb-3">Sync cycle</h3>
        <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">
          <li><strong class="text-gray-300">Push</strong> — After local changes, the app waits 15 seconds (debounce), commits all modified files, and pushes to the remote.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-gray-300">Pull</strong> — On app launch, returning from background, or manual pull-to-refresh, the app fetches from the remote and merges.</li>
          <li>If the merge succeeds cleanly (fast-forward or no conflicts), the working tree is checked out.</li>
          <li>If conflicts are detected, GitSorted resolves them automatically using the strategies below.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-white mt-6 mb-3">Conflict resolution strategies</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-4">Conflicts are resolved automatically — the user is never asked to manually resolve a merge. Three categories are handled:</p>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-lg p-5">
            <h4 class="font-medium text-white mb-2">Both sides modified the same file</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-3">When the same file was edited on both the local device and the remote:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-400 text-sm">
              <li><strong class="text-gray-300">Item files (items/*.json)</strong> — Resolved using the <code class="text-gray-300">conflictStrategy</code> set in <code class="text-gray-300">metadata.json</code>:
                <ul class="mt-1 ml-4 space-y-1">
                  <li><code class="text-gray-300">last-write-wins</code> (default) — The version with the later <code class="text-gray-300">updatedAt</code> timestamp is kept.</li>
                  <li><code class="text-gray-300">remote-wins</code> — The remote version is always kept.</li>
                  <li><code class="text-gray-300">local-wins</code> — The local version is always kept.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong class="text-gray-300">Metadata (metadata.json)</strong> — <strong class="text-white">Union merge.</strong> Labels from both sides are combined and deduplicated. The <code class="text-gray-300">projectType</code> from the remote side is used.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-lg p-5">
            <h4 class="font-medium text-white mb-2">One side deleted, the other edited</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-3">When a file was deleted on one side but modified on the other:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-400 text-sm">
              <li><strong class="text-gray-300">Local delete, remote edit</strong> — <strong class="text-white">Edit wins.</strong> The remote's edited version is restored.</li>
              <li><strong class="text-gray-300">Remote delete, local edit</strong> — <strong class="text-white">Edit wins.</strong> The local edited version is kept.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">In both cases, content preservation takes priority over deletion.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-4">After all conflicts are resolved, a merge commit is created with both parent OIDs, making it a true merge commit (not a rebase or squash).</p>
      </section>

